ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic performance of the surface-coated CA-PDMA, CA-PDMA/TiO2, CA-FNPs and CA-FNPs/TiO2 species on the PET substrate was assessed by the degradation of organic methylene blue (MB) under UV and visible light irradiation (Fig. 7
                     ) [28]. In the presence of UV light, the measured photocatalytic rates of the CA-PDMA/TiO2 and CA-FNPs/TiO2 composites indicated significant photocatalytic activity, which is related to the capability of the materials to degrade MB in a time-dependent manner (Fig. 7a). Using the Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics equation, the photocatalytic reaction was found to obey the pseudo-first order model [29]. The oxidizing agents are usually assumed to promote the photooxidation process, which results in decreasing absorbance of the MB molecules on the surface of the photocatalyst (TiO2). However, in the presence of visible light irradiation, the photocatalytic activity existed only for the CA-FNPs/TiO2 composites (Fig. 7b). Additionally, the photocatalytic degradation of another organic material Rhodamine B showed almost similar results as those observed in previous experiment confirming a generalized photocatalytic platform (Fig. S4). This finding may indicate the possibility of using solar light for TiO2 photocatalytic applications. A possible mechanism may involve carbon derived FNPs serving as electron acceptors and donors, which results in the photo-induced electron recombination from the FNPs to the TiO2 surface and the withdrawal of abundant electrons from the TiO2 to the FNPs surface during photochemical conversion (corresponding to a typical upconversion process) [11]. Actually, electron accepting or donating ability of materials is based on the electronic energy levels of two interacting materials. To examine the general tendency of CA-FNPs in this study, the emission intensities can be quenched by a known electron acceptor 2,4-dinitrotoluene (−0.9 V vs. NHE) and an electron donor N,N-diethylaniline(0.88 V vs. NHE), with observed Stern–Volmer quenching constants (K
                     sv) from linear regression of 31.0 M-1 and 23.4 M-1, respectively (Fig. S5) [30–32]. From the fluorescence quenching examination, it is clear that CA-FNPs can play both roles of donor and acceptor depending on the interacting materials.
